metadata.name: NAKACHOII #112
metadata.description:
*Nakachoii*
The Nakachoii soldiers from anime lands entered fxhash, this time to get new faces and new powers with the coding that is applied to them. Every time they are minted, and every time a new hash is generated, a new power is given to them. The Nakachoii soldier will fit inside your wallet and protect it with these powers. We are very happy that we gained so much experience on fxhash during its first year, and finally, we were able to create a great project based on all these experiences. Nakachoii is ready to create beauty.

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 2 #241
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

metadata.name: Modulation #192
metadata.description:
Isometric cityscapes, patterns and geometries generated by trigonometric functions and rendered as SVG.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000×7500.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: Sweeping #91
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- Double Click to open a User Interface
- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

---

Made with p5js + webgl by Wouter Missler, 2022.

metadata.name: Representation #58
metadata.description:
Explore the world of gender politics through vibrant circles.

Representation is an artwork/data visualization about the gender split in parliaments across the world. 

Each minted artwork gets assigned 6 countries from different regions. 1 country from the Pacific, 1 from Europe, 1 from Asia, 1 from the Americas, 1 from Sub-saharan Africa and 1 from the Middle East and North Africa.

Each circle in your artwork represents the gender split of the parliament(s) in one of those countries by using colors. The legend in the bottom right can be used to decipher which color means what.

This artwork was created using p5js.

The artwork adapts to different screen sizes and ratios, so I exploring it on various devices or resizing your browser window. 

Features:

- Circle Size: What size are the circles?
- Circle Distance: How far apart from each other are the circles?
- Circle Scatter: Are the circles scattered on the Y-axis?

twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art

metadata.name: Fischbach #93
metadata.description:
#fxhashturnsone

The first 365 crazy days of fxhash - time to celebrate this and take a look back.

The entropy of memories in a vivid photo collage that gives me goosebumps while others might just see moving eye candy. Perspective and perception can be so different.

Based on some of my photos from the last 365 days that trigger emotional memories, even if they are not directly connected. By the way, Fischbach is the name of the small village where I grew up. It was a great time!

How does it work?

Each piece uses pairs of photos and colors (top/bottom).

The animated collage itself is based on two layers. The first layer uses a double buffer to cut, colorize and animate the photos. The second layer is mainly just for screen rendering, debugging and behind-the-scene looks.

Cutting and pasting photos is based on a variable moving color grid, the fixed horizon, the variable position of the photos top/bottom, the previous buffer and some magic distance calculations between them.

The grid itself is a combination of vertical color stripes with variable position and distance factors that determine the color gradient between the two colors, and folds that alternate between the two colors depending on the horizontal and vertical values.

Especially the entropy of the photos and the colored grid influence the pixel movement.

Animation changes are triggered after a random number of frames and effect folds, stripes and photo position. These replace parts of the current collage (fade to black) or add some (discard fragment updates).

Features:

- top color [12] - hue, colorful & bright
- bottom color [6] - hue, less colorful & bright
- top photo [16] (zingst, birds, xmas, zustand, zebra, moving-blocks-mono, fischbach, santanyi, goldblume, ♠4, driften, brand-pyramide, zäpfle, bc, tisa, lieblingspulli)
- bottom photo: [16] (zingst, birds, xmas, zustand, zebra, moving-blocks-mono, fischbach, santanyi, goldblume, ♠4, driften, brand-pyramide, zäpfle, bc, tisa, lieblingspulli)
- horizon [0.618, 0.5, 0.382] (down, center, up)
- hectic [3, 5, 11] (calm, slightly, very)
- horizontal folds [113, 365, 997, 2153, 3987] - used for first animation iteration, variable
- vertical folds [7, 37, 127, 571, 1501, 3147] - used for first animation iteration, variable
- min stripes [1, 3, 5] - used for first animation iteration, variable

Animation and feature selection are based on the deterministic prng Xoshiro128 seeded with the fxhash. This allows repeated playback in the same sequence. The animation is synchronized with frames and not with time.

The preview images are taken after 300 frames.

Shortcuts & interactions:

- spacebar, mouse click or tap touch to trigger animation changes
- `c` to take a picture
- `f` for full screen mode
- `p` to pause
- `h` to see all options

Available query string parameters:

- autopause - enable automatic pausing
- pixelratio=2 - sets the pixel ratio (default: device)
- showannouncement - activates the announcement
- kioskspeed=10 - activates the kiosk mode and sets the speed in seconds
- showinfo - activates the info box

metadata.name: soul materium #20
metadata.description:
Today I present to you the "material of the soul".
Artwork generates three-dimensional waves, creating an incredible pattern of matter.

The soul is as important a part of you as the body. Only your soul decides if you like the artwork. She always knows you better than anyone, and no matter how much you deny her desires, she will always be right. She can hurt, love, hope .. Or is it all the same?
